<section class="py-16 bg-white"><div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-12 items-center"><div><h2 class="font-heading text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Why Pavers Work in the Desert</h2><p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Concrete cracks. Asphalt softens in the heat. Pavers flex with the ground, handle thermal expansion, and if one gets damaged you replace that one piece — not the whole surface. They're also permeable when installed with the right jointing, which means better drainage during monsoons.</p><p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">We offer a range of styles — natural stone, concrete pavers, flagstone, and travertine — and David helps you choose what fits your home's style and your budget. The base prep is what makes it last, and we don't cut corners there.</p></div><div><img src="/assets/images/brainards-pavers-1-e0106a00.jpeg" alt="Custom paver patio installation in Las Cruces" width="305" height="331" loading="lazy" class="rounded-xl shadow-lg w-full"></div></div></section>

<section class="py-16 bg-green-50"><div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8"><div class="text-center mb-12"><h2 class="font-heading text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">Paver FAQ</h2></div><div class="space-y-4">
<details class="group bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm"><summary class="flex items-center justify-between p-6 cursor-pointer"><span class="font-heading font-medium text-gray-900">How long do pavers last in the Las Cruces climate?</span><svg class="w-5 h-5 text-green-700 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg></summary><div class="px-6 pb-6 text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Decades. Quality pavers on a proper base handle the heat, UV, and freeze-thaw cycles without cracking. The base prep and edge restraints are what determine longevity — that's where we spend the most attention.</div></details>
<details class="group bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm"><summary class="flex items-center justify-between p-6 cursor-pointer"><span class="font-heading font-medium text-gray-900">Can you match pavers to my existing hardscape?</span><svg class="w-5 h-5 text-green-700 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg></summary><div class="px-6 pb-6 text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Usually yes. We work with multiple suppliers and can get close matches for color and texture. David will bring samples to your property so you can see them against your existing walls, borders, and home exterior before committing.</div></details>
<details class="group bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm"><summary class="flex items-center justify-between p-6 cursor-pointer"><span class="font-heading font-medium text-gray-900">Pavers or poured concrete — which is better?</span><svg class="w-5 h-5 text-green-700 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg></summary><div class="px-6 pb-6 text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Pavers cost more upfront but are more durable in the desert — they flex along with soil movement rather than fracturing, and individual pavers can be replaced if needed. Poured concrete is cheaper but more prone to cracking over time. David will recommend what makes sense for your specific project.</div></details>
</div></div></section>

